        <Historic_Flag>Current</Historic_Flag>
        <Parent_String>volcanic glass [300263800], pyroclastic rock [300011253], extrusive rock [300011246], igneous rock by origin [300011243], igneous rock [300011178], rock (inorganic material) [300011692], inorganic material [300010360], materials by composition [300212963], materials (substances) [300010358], Materials (hierarchy name) [300010357], Materials Facet [300264091]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>A volcanic glass that contains about 75% silica and usually has a higher water content than obsidian; found in Oregon and California. Commercially, the term refers to volcanic glass that will expand or "pop" when heated to form a lightweight aggregate.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099620/Legacy AAT data</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Vidrio volcánico que contiene aproximadamente 75% de sílice y habitualmente un contenido de agua superior al de la obsidiana. Se encuentra en Oregón y California. Comercialmente, el término se refiere al vidrio volcánico que se expande o "se infla" al calentarlo, formando un agregado liviano.
</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Vulkaanglas dat circa 75% silica bevat en gewoonlijk een hoger watergehalte heeft dan obsidiaan; aangetroffen in Oregon en Californië. In commercieel opzicht verwijst de term naar vulkaanglas dat uitzet of ploft wanneer het wordt verwarmd, waarbij een samengestelde stof ontstaat met een laag gewicht.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052381/Van Dale Engels-Nederlands (1989)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>一種火山玻璃，含有約75%的矽，通常比黑曜岩含有更多水分。美國奧瑞岡州（Oregon）和加州皆可見到此種岩石。商業用語中，此詞彙意指加熱形成輕集料時會膨脹或嗶啵迸開的火山玻璃。 </Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
